\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Magnitude of non-climate prediction adjustments to SOC mean transit time.} Per-pixel absolute difference between each process-group model and the climate-only baseline ($|M_i - M_1|$, in years), rendered as a CMY subtractive colour composite: cyan\nobreakspace  {}$= |M_2 - M_1|$ (Edaphic), magenta\nobreakspace  {}$= |M_3 - M_1|$ (Land Use), yellow\nobreakspace  {}$= |M_4 - M_1|$ (Biological). Channel intensities are normalised to the 98th percentile of the pooled three-group distribution (29.0\nobreakspace  {}yr) and mapped to 0--255. White indicates regions where climate alone explains most of the prediction (little non-climate adjustment in any channel); mixed hues indicate co-modulation (blue\nobreakspace  {}$=$\nobreakspace  {}Edaphic+LandUse, red\nobreakspace  {}$=$\nobreakspace  {}LandUse+Biological, green\nobreakspace  {}$=$\nobreakspace  {}Edaphic+Biological); saturated/black indicates strong simultaneous modulation by all three groups. A luminance modulation (blend strength\nobreakspace  {}0.6) additionally washes regions toward white where total non-climate adjustment is small, emphasising regions with substantive non-climate signal. This figure shows the \emph  {magnitude} of local prediction adjustment, not statistical dominance or variance explained; for variance partitioning see Table\nobreakspace  {}\ref {tab:model_comparison} and Fig.\nobreakspace  {}\ref {fig:importance}. Predictions at 0.1\textdegree {} aggregated to 0.5\textdegree {}; borders from Natural Earth 1:50\,m. }}{30}{figure.5}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:process_contribution}{{5}{30}{\textbf {Magnitude of non-climate prediction adjustments to SOC mean transit time.} Per-pixel absolute difference between each process-group model and the climate-only baseline ($|M_i - M_1|$, in years), rendered as a CMY subtractive colour composite: cyan~$= |M_2 - M_1|$ (Edaphic), magenta~$= |M_3 - M_1|$ (Land Use), yellow~$= |M_4 - M_1|$ (Biological). Channel intensities are normalised to the 98th percentile of the pooled three-group distribution (29.0~yr) and mapped to 0--255. White indicates regions where climate alone explains most of the prediction (little non-climate adjustment in any channel); mixed hues indicate co-modulation (blue~$=$~Edaphic+LandUse, red~$=$~LandUse+Biological, green~$=$~Edaphic+Biological); saturated/black indicates strong simultaneous modulation by all three groups. A luminance modulation (blend strength~0.6) additionally washes regions toward white where total non-climate adjustment is small, emphasising regions with substantive non-climate signal. This figure shows the \emph {magnitude} of local prediction adjustment, not statistical dominance or variance explained; for variance partitioning see Table~\ref {tab:model_comparison} and Fig.~\ref {fig:importance}. Predictions at 0.1\textdegree {} aggregated to 0.5\textdegree {}; borders from Natural Earth 1:50\,m}{figure.5}{}}
